metadata.name: Memory #164
metadata.description:
"Memory" is an experiment in the dynamic interplay of soulful colors and forms. 
It is an exploration of smooth animation blending interesting fluid shapes. 
The piece is a continuous flow of forms and hues that seamlessly transition. 
The viewer can interactively zoom in and out and navigate to explore the full space of the artwork.
Furthermore the aspect ratio can be change to vary the framing of the piece, generating new impressions.
This invites the viewer to fully immerse themselves in the piece and experience it from different perspectives.
The name "Memory" reflects the intention to display an abstract representation of memories of a machine.
The colors aim to evoke a sense of emotion and depth. 

I created this work using twgl.js on a single fragment shader, my recent technique of choice. 

I hope you enjoy interacting with "Memory" and exploring the different aspects of the piece.

This piece uses webgl, it can thus only be viewed on browsers implementing webgl.

License: CC-BY-NC-SA 4.0
Dependencies: 
- twgljs - A Tiny WebGL helper Library (MIT license)
- psrdnoise.glsl (MIT license)
- isMobile (Unlicense)
For more information, view the license file

Interactions
'-' to zoom in. 
'+' to zoom out.
'f' to change the aspect ratio to fullscreen.
'1' to change the aspect ratio to square.
'a' to change the aspect ratio to portrait format.
'w' to change the aspect ratio to 16:9.
's' to save an image of the canvas.
't' to toggle the time (day/night) in the image.
'b' to toggle the frame.
'h' to increase the quality modifier (maximum is 3).
'l' to decrease the quality modifier (minimum is 1).
The quality modifier is a modifier on the width and height of the canvas.
Changing the modifier can affect the look of the image due to subpixel artifacts.
The modifier can be used to save higher resolution images.
Higher values of the modifier increase memory usage and can cause a browser or webgl instance to crash.
'arrow_up' to move up in the image.
'arrow_down' to move down in the image.
'arrow_right' to move right in the image.
'arrow_left' to move left in the image.

metadata.name: Light Years Away #216
metadata.description:
The individual, sitting alone in an abandoned castle, reflects on their past and experiences a sense of collapse and confusion. The once grand halls are now overrun with moss and ancient porcelain scattered throughout the corners, seemingly mocking their current state of mind. However, a ray of light shines through as the clouds part, signaling hope for the future. Through collapse and confusion, the individual strives for peace and freedom, standing with renewed determination and a new perspective.

metadata.name: paintflow #99
metadata.description:
For this project, I wanted to try out Ty Vek's SVG technique for creating gen art. I used some basic SVG filters to achieve the paint brush effect, then just added some simple line and curve patterns. The result is quite nice and organic feeling! There are only 2 colors: red and black - I felt it was important to focus on the shapes and lines rather than the colors. The number of curves varies from 2 to 4, and each can be filled above or below. That's the gist of it! I hope you get some pretty pieces.

You can save the generated SVG by pressing the 's' key, and you can save a PNG version by pressing the 'p' key.

Please enjoy!

metadata.name: Fifty Windows #27
metadata.description:
"Fifty Windows" is a minimal generative art project that explores thoughts and feelings around the theme of life's choices, by symbolically representing the idea of looking through a window to the other side, where there are all the opportunities and life experiences that we could have missed.

But the other side of the window also represent the idea of a gaze that looks out, where one can explore different life experiences and new paths of growth and fulfillment.

The project is also focused on the idea of perspective, that is allowed by the minimalistic tracts of the artworks, that make you understand that you’re in front of a windows, but you’re never sure if you're looking in or out.

Just like in life, sometimes we may be on one side of the window, feeling like we've missed something, while other times we're living something that others may be regretting.

Life is just a game of perspectives.

- - -

To save artworks at high resolution press "s" in live mode and wait :)

metadata.name: Iteration is Usually Recursive (Pt. 1) #134
metadata.description:
This is the companion piece released with 'Iteration is Usually Recursive — Introduction: Finding answers in pre-computational art', the first in a series of essays, some long, some short, on generative art, theory and the practitioners of the medium. 

This piece started a simple experimen recreating George Nees’ Schotter (1968)— a classic piece of generative art history — as vanilla js SVG graphics. From there, I specifically developed it with non-plotter printing in mind, and more specific still, Riso Printing (think a scanner with a digital screen-printer MacGyver’d on). The palettes are taken from hex-estimated Risograph colour gamuts, with three layers being multiplied together to replicate, to some degree, the blending of the semi-transparent Risographic inks. Within this study, there’s a few different things going on, the initial setup is rectangles which cascade down the canvas, inheriting more extreme rotation as they get closer to the bottom (a la Schotter). The second is a subdivision of the shapes with filled circled, outlined circles and squares — since in this study the base shapes are rectangles and not squares, distribution of the ‘dithering’ can be larger than a single ‘pixel’ size — when these multiple layers overlap, the shapes produce a halftone-moire effect, forms and structures appear from the noise as the underlying patterns intersect. 

tx: Who?, Cosimo, Liam Egan, Andreas Rau, Louis

Licensing: CC-BY-NC-ND

metadata.name: Livro #118
metadata.description:
A messy book is a well-read book, a sign of knowledge acquired. It's easy to spot a book that has been loved and used frequently. The pages are bent and creased, the spine is worn, and notes are scribbled in the margins. These imperfections are not a sign of neglect or carelessness, but rather an evidence of a book that has been fully engaged with and understood.
A book that is kept in pristine condition may look nice on a shelf, but it is also a sign that it has not been read as much, or not as deeply. A well-read book is an indication of a curious and active mind, always seeking to learn and grow. So, don't be afraid to let your books get a little messy, it's a sign that you're gaining knowledge and expanding your understanding of the world around you.

Made with p5.js, p5.grain and much love <3

[S] to save as image

metadata.name: fields, sketches #109
metadata.description:
The third and final part of our generative sketchbook of ideas for a sculpture garden.

Fields builds off Stan Allen's seminal essay "Field Conditions" in which he laid out a prototypical theory of architectural field schemes. Field Conditions are opposed to figural or object-based compositional strategies and approach a site from a systemic point of view. These fields contain a range of possible wall-types. Some produce enclosures, while others dictate a wandering path.

Built with p5.js
By office ca
2022

metadata.name: Aging and Forgotten #16
metadata.description:
"Aging and Forgotten" is my tribute to the transience of technology and life. In this exhibit, I bring together a collection of discarded technological devices and symbols of aging and death, such as skulls and bones. My goal is to create a powerful commentary on the impermanence of all things and the parallel between the aging of technology and the aging of people. Through the combination of technology and the human, I invite viewers to reflect on their own experiences of aging, loss, and the passage of time. With "Aging and Forgotten," I aim to challenge viewers to consider the impact of our rapidly advancing technology and the ultimate fate of all things, both human and technological.

- look for the gold mode
- press p to export png
- press s to export svg

metadata.name: The Beauty of Discord #96
metadata.description:
This experimental artwork is a unique blend of human and machine inputs, showcasing the potential for collaboration between the two in the creative process. The human component of the piece is evident in the deliberate composition, choice of color, and the use of painting algorithms. Meanwhile, the machine component is represented by two powerful AI technologies. The first, ChatGPT3, generated a thought-provoking poem about the galaxies and cosmos, serving as the inspiration for the piece. The second, DALL-E 2, then used this poem as a prompt to create a stunning AI image, bringing the cosmic themes to life in a realistic and captivating way.

The combination of these two AI technologies, along with the human touch in the painting algorithms and composition, creates an artwork that is truly one-of-a-kind. The final product is not only visually stunning, but it also serves as a glimpse into the future of humanity and the possibilities of AI collaboration in art. The artwork is a testament to the beauty that can result from a seemingly discordant combination of human and machine inputs, and it invites us to consider the impact of technology on the creative process and the role of the human artist in the age of AI.

Press a to see the AI-generated image.
Press g to switch back to the paint.
